<p>I would reccomend using the <a href="https://first.wpi.edu/wpilib/allwpilib/docs/release/java/edu/wpi/first/wpilibj/Timer.html" class="inline-onebox" rel="noopener nofollow ugc">Timer (WPILib API 2021.3.1)</a> class and setting your is finished condition to timer.hasElapsed(seconds). That seems more maintainable and clear than what you have here. Or, you can just make a command that runs the motor what whatever speed and use a .withTimeout(seconds) command decorator as you need <a href="https://docs.wpilib.org/en/stable/docs/software/commandbased/convenience-features.html#command-decorator-methods" rel="noopener nofollow ugc">Convenience Features — FIRST Robotics Competition documentation (wpilib.org)</a>.</p>","post_number":10,"post_type":1,"posts_count":13,"updated_at":"2021-10-30T00:06:58.881Z","reply_count":0,"reply_to_post_number":8,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":4,"reads":130,"readers_count":129,"score":121.0,"yours":false,"topic_id":396908,"topic_slug":"run-motor-for-1-second-then-stop","display_username":"","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":2,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"link_counts":[{"url":"https://first.wpi.edu/wpilib/allwpilib/docs/release/java/edu/wpi/first/wpilibj/Timer.html","internal":false,"reflection":false,"title":"Timer (WPILib API 2021.3.1)","clicks":15},{"url":"https://docs.wpilib.org/en/stable/docs/software/commandbased/convenience-features.html#command-decorator-methods","internal":false,"reflection":false,"title":"Convenience Features — FIRST Robotics Competition documentation","clicks":7}],"read":true,"user_title":"","reply_to_user":{"id":17356,"username":"Ian_McTavish","name":"Ian McTavish","avatar_template":"/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/i/b5a626/{size}.png"},"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[{"id":2,"count":2}],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":34970,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":""},"post_url":"/t/run-motor-for-1-second-then-stop/396908/10","custom_user_title":null,"reactions":[{"id":"heart","type":"emoji","count":3}],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":2,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":null},{"id":2974144,"name":"James","username":"otherguy","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/otherguy/{size}/180121_2.png","created_at":"2021-10-30T06:36:44.821Z","cooked":"<p>Others have covered more conventional ways of achieving your goals (command based programming) and using sensor feedback - considering these recommendations will help you long term.</p>
<hr>
<p>Looking at the javadoc for Timer:  <a href="https://first.wpi.edu/wpilib/allwpilib/docs/release/java/edu/wpi/first/wpilibj/Timer.html" class="inline-onebox" rel="noopener nofollow ugc">Timer (WPILib API 2023.4.3)</a></p>
<ul>
<li>the <code>reset()</code> method will set the timer to zero, <strong>but it won’t start the timer</strong>.<br>
make sure you run <code>m_timer.start()</code> earlier in your code so that your timer instance is actually accumulating over time (counting up)</li>
</ul>
<aside class="quote no-group" data-username="Konnor" data-post="1" data-topic="396908">
<div class="title">
