<img loading="lazy" alt="" width="24" height="24" src="https://www.chiefdelphi.com/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/konnor/48/246214_2.png" class="avatar"> Konnor:</div>
<blockquote>
<pre data-code-wrap="java"><code class="lang-java">if (m_timer.get() &gt; 1.0) {
  m_motor.set(1);
}
else if (m_timer.get() &lt; 1.0) {
  m_motor.set(0);
}
</code></pre>
</blockquote>
</aside>
<p>If the logic isn’t doing what you expect it might be helpful to try to add print statements into your code to help you troubleshoot it. Something like:</p>
<pre><code class="lang-auto">double current_time = m_timer.get();

System.out.print("current_time=" + current_time + ", ");
if (current_time  &gt; 1.0) {
  m_motor.set(1);
  System.out.println("setting motor on");
}
else if (current_time  &lt; 1.0) {
  m_motor.set(0);
  System.out.println("setting motor off");
}
</code></pre>
<p>to my eye it looks like you’ve got the following, which I don’t think is what you describe in your first post</p>
<pre><code class="lang-auto">if (m_timer.get() &gt; 1.0) {
  // turn motor on if more than 1.0s has elapsed since the timer was reset
  m_motor.set(1);
}
else if (m_timer.get() &lt; 1.0) {
  // turn motor off if less than 1.0s has elapsed since the timer was reset
  m_motor.set(0);
}
</code></pre>
<p>Also just a suggestion on programming style to make your code more clear &amp; safe:<br>
If you find yourself in a scenario where you have two distinct (mutually exclusive) possible outcomes, write it w/ a simple if/else block. This style will remove opportunity for none of your conditional statements being qualified. e.g.</p>
<pre><code class="lang-auto">if time elapsed is less than one second
  turn motor on
else
  turn motor off
</code></pre>
